Abia state commissioner for Information, Chief Okiyi Kalu has said that although there had not been a single case of Coronvarius case in the state, the government had been stepping up campaign against it. Kalu stated this during an interaction with newsmen at the Nigeria Union of Journalists (NUJ) secretariat in Umuahia, the state capital, saying the government is preparing as if the virus is pushing on their doors. He expressed concern that there are only three testing centres for the virus in the country, adding that the government was making arrangement to procure three machines for the three senatorial districts in the state. According to him, even ahead of the outbreak of the virus, the government had been very proactive in protecting the health of the people which include the Tele health initiative and home health care for the elderly. The explained that even the tele health initiative which he said has four motorized clinics, seven ambulances and eight medical doctors on standby could be used for emergencies for the virus. He admonished the people against panic measures, which he said could be detrimental, adding that the government was not considering closure of schools or placing of limits to public gathering. The commissioner who argued that rather, the government had mounted robust campaign against the spread of the virus stressed that people should engage in serious personal and communal hygiene to avoid the virus.